                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d16">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European Advisory Commission/60:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-28T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 28, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>701. Inasmuch as the paper on French Civil Affairs (your 544, January 20,<note
                        n="43" xml:id="d16fn43">See footnote 42, above.</note> and 632, January 24)
                    was referred by the Moscow Conference to the European Advisory Commission, our
                    view is that the paper is now formally before the Commission by reference from
                    Moscow, and you are authorized to discuss it on the basis of your present
                    instructions. If the Russians have any important objections, they will no doubt
                    be developed in the course of the discussions, and we can consider them upon
                    report from you.</p>
                <p>Should there be any fundamental change here, such as envisaged in your 632 of
                    January 24, you will be promptly informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
